frameDefinitions: An Agent acts according to a Plan, carrying it out (or taking steps to carry it out).
A Controlling_entity, Controlling_situation, or Controlling_variable control a Dependent_entity, Dependent_situation, or Dependent_variable.
An Agent matches location with an Entity in order to fulfill some  Purpose.
An Executive_authority exchanges one penalty, the Original_punishment, for another less severe one, the New_punishment.
An intentional Agent or a causing event (Cause) event causes a Theme which is already in motion to take a different Path or Direction, or reach a different Goal than the Original_path.
A Questioner asks a Witness (or defendant) questions in the context of a court procedure.
frameExamples: Health authorities say they have put measures into <t>effect</t> in all ports of entry and in centers of provinces.
I ca n't remember how many times he <t>visited</t> ! DNI
On December 15, 1971, Governor Winfield Dunn conditionally <t>commuted</t> his sentence to twenty years.

The hotel business didn't last - especially after the construction of a railroad
<t>diverted</t> travelers a few miles west to what is now the village of Eagle
We 'd like to <t>cross-examine</t> the witness if we can.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Plan</fen> is a goal or purpose that the <fen>Agent</fen> carries out.

The <fen>Agent</fen>, often an institution or governmental organization, puts a <fen>Plan</fen> into effect. The Agent is generally a primary participant in the <fen>Plan</fen>, but a separate <fen>Focal_participant</fen> may be specified.
This role describes the medium through which a plan was executed.  It may occur in the same syntactic position as the Agent.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which the Agent puts the <fen>Plan</fen> into effect.

The <fen>Place</fen> at which the <fen>Plan</fen> is or is not operational.

[CHANGE: or, place where agent puts into effect? 2 fes?]
A thing or person whose behavior controls a <fen>Dependent_entity</fen>, <fen>Dependent_situation</fen>, or <fen>Dependent_variable</fen>.
An entity, usually a thing, that is influenced in its behavior by a <fen>Controlling_entity</fen> or an <fen>Controlling_situation</fen>.
A scalar variable (with unspecified value) which has an effect on the <fen>Dependent_entity</fen>, <fen>Dependent_situation</fen>, or <fen>Dependent_variable</fen>.
A situation whose temporal or other characteristics are influenced by a <fen>Controlling_entity</fen>, <fen>Controlling_situation</fen>, or <fen>Controlling_variable</fen>.
A scalar variable, whose value depends on the behavior of a <fen>Controlling_entity</fen>, a <fen>Controlling_situation</fen>, or a <fen>Controlling_variable</fen>.
A situation whose temporal or other characteristics control a <fen>Dependent_entity</fen>, <fen>Dependent_situation</fen>, or <fen>Dependent_variable</fen>.
The <fex name='deg'>Degree</fex> to which the Controlling element affects the Dependent element.
The <fex name='tim'>Time</fex> at which the controlling occurs.
The location at which the controlling occurs.
The sentient entity that is temporarily with the <fen>Entity</fen> in order to fulfil some <fen>Purpose</fen>.

The physical entity that is permanently associated with entities or characteristics that the <fen>Agent</fen> wishes to use for some <fen>Purpose</fen>.  During the visit, the <fen>Agent</fen> matches location with the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The time at which a visit is made.
A description of the position of the <fen>Agent</fen> during the visit.
The constitutionally specified authority who has the power to commute punishments.
The punishment the <fen>Offender</fen> was originally sentenced to.
The time at which the <fen>Original_punishment</fen>  is commuted.
The location where the <fen>Executive_authority</fen> commutes the <fen>Original_punishment</fen>.
The entity that is in motion, and changes path due to the action of an Agent or due to a Cause.

The route that the <fen>Theme</fen> was originally headed for.  In cases when the <fen>Theme</fen> is an intentional actor or is controlled by an intentional actor, the <fen>Original_path</fen> correlates with the (former) plan of the actor.  In other cases, the <fen>Original_path</fen> corresponds to what would be expected for the path of the <fen>Theme</fen> from general principles or physics.  (In some cases, the <fen>Original_path</fen> may indicate the intended destination, and not just the path, of the <fen>Theme</fen>.)
The <fen>Path</fen> refers to (a part of) the ground over which the <fen>Theme</fen> ends up travelling after being diverted.
The location the <fen>Theme</fen> ends up in after being redirected.

This role is used for expressions that indicate motion along a line from the current deitic center towards a reference point (which may be implicit) that does not necessarily correspond to the <fen>Goal</fen>.  Often <fen>Direction</fen> is defined with reference to the canonical orientation of the <fen>Theme</fen>, the orientation imposed by an implicit observer, or the inherent orientation of the scene.
An individual that determines the change in course of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
An event that brings about the change in the <fen>Path</fen> of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the redirection of motion occurs.
The <fen>Place</fen> is the location at which the redirection occurs.
The individual who asks a <fen>Witness</fen> questions.
A person who is present in a courtroom in order to give some form of evidence, has been sworn in, and is being examined by a <fen>Questioner</fen>.
When the examination occurs.
Where the examination takes place.
